|RUSSIAN ARTICLES: &cr;&lf;&cr;&lf;There are no definite or indefinite articles (such as the, a, an in English) in the Russian language.&cr;&lf;&cr;&lf;- do show that it is definite or undefinite they change the objects ending (a book/the book - ви́жу/кни́ги)&cr;&lf;- the use of the numeral one sometimes signifies that the noun is indefinite (I met one (=a) friend)&cr;&lf;- Word order may also be used for this purpose&cr;&lf;- The plural form may signify indefiniteness|

|RUSSIAN VERBS: &cr;&lf;&cr;&lf;Russian has only one present tense&cr;&lf;only one way of saying "I work", "I am working" and "I do work"|

|Russian verbs change their endings depending on the subject. This happens a little in English, but not as much. (Example: I work, he works). This happens according to two different patterns known as the first conjugation, and the second conjugation. (There are also some irregular verbs)|
